            <p>This article gives an overview of selected literary works that narrate instances of historical complicity in the Central East European contexts, and makes a series of original observations about the prevalence or a 'wave' of such literary representations in the 21st century European literature. The article anchors its detailed analyses of two literary texts in a theoretical and philosophic literature in memory and post-memory studies, trans-generational trauma theory, and testimonial theory (to mention just those). The concept of complicity is well outlined and the argument for the importance of literary accounts of complicity (by way of addressing structural and conceptual limitations of the juridical discourse on complicity) is persuasive. I have also enjoyed and learnt from the author's eloquent analyses of Jelinek's 
                <italic>Rechnitz </italic>and Fritsch's 
                <italic>Hertzklappen</italic>.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Hence, the problem with the article is not the content or its conceptualisation, but, rather, its framing as presented in the opening sections. In my view, the article promises to do something else than it actually does - the opening questions about the present-day cultural traction of literary representations of complicity and its purport to the contemporary reader are not answered. Rather, the analytic focus throughout is on the aesthetic strategies of distanciation, and how these overlap and imbricate with the politics and ethics of (self) separation from difficult history. The opening point about what the author calls 'convergence' &#x00a0;(between historical complicity and the complexities of participation in exploitative economic, social and economic structures today) thus disappears in the main section of the article. My suggestion would be to re-frame the article so that it starts off with articulating the problem that it actually addresses and persuasively argues - how selected works of literature replicate and implement aesthetics of patio-temporal and moral distanciation, and how other literary works subvert and resist them.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> I also wonder (though could be convinced otherwise) whether this arrangement of two primary analyses (Fritsch and Jelinek) isn't somewhat too binary and too oppositional - one text is clearly presented as replicating problematic aesthetics of distanciation and the other as subverting them. In this binary, the references to Stepanova's 
                <italic>In Memory of Memory</italic> are pushed to the periphery of the paper, but the author's insight is fascinating and left me wanting to read more. Perhaps it would be possible to give a more prominent place in the article to&#x00a0;Stepanova so that there is a detailed analysis of three literary works, and not two, and the author explored how the subversion or 'undoing' of the strategies of distanciation happens in Stepanova? It might be an issue of a word count to extend the paper in this way, but might be worthwhile to consider.&#x00a0;</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Finally, I also want to point to a number of places in the paper where interesting formulations are somewhat underdeveloped&#x00a0;and could benefit from more elaboration, or where turns of an argument are too abrupt: 
                <list list-type="bullet">
                    <list-item>
                        <p>The reference to the point on 'totalitarianism' on pp. 7 &amp; 8 comes and ends too abruptly; could it be folded more onto the analysis?</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>The reference to Bacchae, and its relevance for the author's analysis of Jelinek needs more development; it intrigues, but its significance is somewhat elusive.</p>
                    </list-item>
                </list> For the discussion of Arendt's point from 
                <italic>Responsibility and Judgment</italic>, see also Arendt's rather little-discussed short text "Answers to Questions Submitted by Samuel Grafton" (included in 
                <italic>The Jewish Writings</italic> collections ed. by Kohn and Feldman), where she develops the point on guilt and responsibility.
                <sup>
                    <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="rep-ref-28999-1">1</xref>
                </sup>
            </p>
