                            <p>I have expanded the signposting explaining why I juxtapose Fritsch&#x2019;s and Jelinek&#x2019;s text, and I have added a note to my detailed discussion of Stepanova elsewhere (which is the reason why I did not expand it is this paper).</p>
                        </list-item>
                        <list-item>
                            <p>I have, as noted in the general point, substantially expanded the discussion of totalitarianism. I have expanded the explanation of the reference to Bacchae to explain how it relates to the issue of complicity and distance.</p>
                        </list-item>
                        <list-item>
                            <p>I am also thankful for making me aware of Arendt&#x2019;s text of her Eichmann book. However, I have not included it because a) the discussion of guilt and responsibility of Eichmann refers to an individual rather than the relational aspect I want to focus on, and b) the tremendously difficult question of the Judenr&#x00e4;te discussed in Arendt would require a detailed discussion that would go beyond the scope of my article. But I will certainly come back to the text in my further work.</p>
