            <p>This article explores the reflection on complicity in terror and perpetration across Eastern and Central European literatures. It is highly original in its operationalisation of complicity, which is first and foremost presented as a legal concept, in a narratological context. The analysis is particularly convincing where it demonstrates how literary narratives can involve readers, but also offer ways of distancing them from the perpetration that the texts refer to. Examples like Valerie Fritsch' 
