                <italic>Dunkelblum</italic>&#x00a0;demonstrate how narrative strategies of spatial, temporal and moral distancing create an effect of reassuring consolation for the reader, where a text addresses collective complicity in atrocities committed within totalitarian rule. Finally, the author shows how Elfriede Jelinek's&#x00a0;
                <italic>Rechnitz (Der W&#x00fc;rgeengel)&#x00a0;</italic>consciously avoids such consolation as it exposes how readers / the audience themselves become complicit when they voyeuristically enjoy the narrative engagement with atrocities of the past.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Similar to the first peer reviewer, I believe that the article is convincing in its main points, but the argument about the reasons for the current rise in interest about atrocities during Nazi and Soviet rule needs to be rethought. It features prominently in the abstract, the introduction and the conclusion, but is not sufficiently addressed in the main part of the article. Generally, the text is quite ambitious despite it being a relatively short essay of roughly 5000 words. While the general concept is strong, some of the examples for distancing effects are only presented very briefly and a more extensive discussion of the literary texts the author refers to would help to carve out these ideas more clearly.</p>
