            <p>The article inquires into the functions of contemporary documentary fictions that engage with the horrors of the Third Reich and Soviet Union. By drawing on a legal category, complicity, the author offers a highly original approach to evaluating ethical attitudes implicit in documentary fiction. While the concept occupies a marginal position in legal discourse, complicity becomes analytically fertile when applied to the realm of fictional settings that shape the collective memory.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The author&#x2019;s case examples include Jachym Topol&#x2019;s 
                <italic>The Devil&#x2019;s Workshop</italic>, Valerie Fritsch&#x2019;s 
                <italic>Herzklappen von Johnson &amp; Johnson</italic>, Maria Stepanova&#x2019;s 
                <italic>In Memory of Memory</italic> and Elfriede Jelinek&#x2019;s 
                <italic>Rechnitz</italic>, the main focus being placed on Fritsch and Jelinek. Accordingly, Fritsch&#x2019;s text, irrespective of its poetic qualities, exemplifies an ethical stance that problematically continues the aggressor&#x2019;s perspective. During the narrator&#x2019;s journeys through Eastern Europe, its territories remain faceless places deprived of socio-political agency. The author&#x2019;s strong criticism of Fritsch is supported by enlightening references to Stepanova. One can only agree with the author&#x2019;s argument. The text&#x2019;s narrator keeps a safe distance from the events of the past, a stance that is afforded by the elision of the East&#x2019;s agency and present-day reality.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> By way of contrast, the author singles out Jelinek&#x2019;s play as a glowing example of a more truthful engagement with the past. In her account of the Rechnitz massacre, justificatory discourses take centre stage. Rhetoric cliches are not only instrumental in deflecting guilt, but are intrinsically linked to a questionable aesthetics of dramatic jouissance, originating in Greek antiquity. While the reviewer does not agree with the author&#x2019;s idea that Jelinek&#x2019;s drama lacks a self-righteous &#x201c;moral high ground&#x201d;, this benevolent assessment is well-accepted in academe and does not need any further explanation.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The only reservation concerns an idea that is, although prominent in the abstract, only faintly sketched in the main argument: the hypothesis &#x201c;that the texts address convergences between involvements in past acts of mass violence and current forms of participation in wrongdoings in neoliberalism&#x201d; (p. 1). In this argument, the distinctions between totalitarianism and neoliberalism are flattened through a sweeping generalisation: Since both forms of government require the individual's complicity in oppression, argues the author, totalitarian and neoliberal modernity must be considered continuities. (The critical reference to this notion is Dupuy 2016.) Even in Neomarxist thought, this makes for an unusual argument, as it goes against basic assumptions in political science. In fact, classic liberalists like Hayek regard the welfare state as more closely linked to totalitarianism than neoliberalism. (See Thomas Biebricher, 
                <italic>The Political Theory of Neoliberalism</italic>, Stanford: Stanford UP, 2018, pp. 18&#x2013;21.) While nothing speaks against expanding on this provocative statement, it would require substantial discussion. This argument is not central to the paper. For the sake of clarity, the author should either elaborate on this argument or remove it.</p>
